Secrets, connection strings, A-P-I keys, certificates, and encryption keys are the most sensitive assets in any cloud application. Azure provides two complementary services to manage them securely. Azure Key Vault is a managed H-S-M-backed store for secrets, keys, and certificates — applications retrieve credentials at runtime rather than embedding them in code or configuration files. Managed Identities give Azure resources such as V-Ms, App Services, and A-K-S pods an identity in Entra I-D so they can authenticate to Key Vault and other services without any stored credentials. Together they eliminate the fundamental credential management problem: how does an application authenticate without storing a password somewhere?

Let us start with Azure Key Vault.

Key Vault comes in three tiers. The Standard tier uses software-protected key storage and is suitable for general-purpose use. The Premium tier backs keys with a Hardware Security Module that meets F-I-P-S 140-2 Level 2 — required for regulated industries and compliance scenarios. The Managed H-S-M tier provides a dedicated single-tenant H-S-M at F-I-P-S 140-2 Level 3 — the highest assurance level, where you have full ownership of the keys and Azure has no access.

Key Vault stores three types of objects. Secrets, Keys, and Certificates — each with its own A-P-I and permission roles.

Secrets store any sensitive string value: database connection strings, A-P-I keys, passwords, and storage account keys. Secrets are versioned — every update creates a new version, and previous versions remain accessible by specifying their version I-D. Each version can have an optional activation date and expiry date. Soft-delete is enabled by default — deleted secrets are retained for 7 to 90 days and can be recovered during that period.

Keys are cryptographic keys used for encrypt, decrypt, sign, and verify operations. The critical property of Key Vault Keys is that the key material never leaves Key Vault. Your application does not download the key — it calls the Key Vault A-P-I and Key Vault performs the operation on your behalf. This is the design that makes customer-managed keys secure: Azure services like Cosmos D-B, S-Q-L Database, and Blob Storage call Key Vault to wrap and unwrap their data encryption keys. Key types include R-S-A in 2048, 3072, and 4096-bit variants, Elliptic Curve keys using P-256, P-384, or P-521 curves, and symmetric A-E-S keys available in H-S-M and Managed H-S-M tiers.

Certificates store X.509 T-L-S and S-S-L certificates. Key Vault can generate a self-signed certificate, issue a certificate through a partner Certificate Authority integration with DigiCert or GlobalSign — where Key Vault creates the certificate signing request, submits it to the C-A, and imports the signed certificate automatically — or import an existing certificate from a P-F-X or P-E-M file. Key Vault supports automatic renewal of certificates before expiry — you configure a trigger such as renew 30 days before expiration and Key Vault handles the renewal workflow.

Now let us look at the permission model.

Key Vault supports two permission models. The legacy Vault Access Policy model grants coarse-grained permissions per vault per identity — for example, an identity is allowed to Get and List secrets across the entire vault. This model is not recommended for new deployments. The Azure R-B-A-C model uses fine-grained roles with Entra I-D integration and is the recommended approach. It allows you to grant precise permissions at the vault level or even at the level of individual secrets or keys.

The built-in R-B-A-C roles for Key Vault are: Key Vault Administrator for full management of all object types and vault settings; Key Vault Secrets Officer for creating, reading, updating, and deleting secrets; Key Vault Secrets User for reading secrets only — this is the role you assign to application identities; Key Vault Keys Officer for managing keys; Key Vault Crypto User for using keys for cryptographic operations without being able to manage them; Key Vault Certificate Officer for managing certificates; and Key Vault Reader for reading vault metadata without access to the actual secret or key values.

For network security, always use a private endpoint in production. A private endpoint assigns Key Vault a private I-P address within your V-Net and the fully qualified domain name resolves to that private I-P through the privatelink dot vaultcore dot azure dot net D-N-S zone. Traffic never crosses the public internet.

Enable purge protection alongside soft-delete for any vault used with customer-managed keys. Purge protection prevents any identity — including subscription administrators — from permanently deleting objects before the retention period expires. This is a hard requirement for C-M-K scenarios because if your Key Vault key is accidentally purged, the encrypted data becomes permanently unrecoverable.

Enable the AuditEvent diagnostic log on every Key Vault and send it to Log Analytics. This records every access to every secret, key, and certificate — who accessed it, when, and from which I-P address. You can then write K-Q-L alerts to detect unusual access patterns such as a large number of secret reads from an unexpected I-P.

Now let us look at Managed Identities.

A Managed Identity is an automatically managed service principal in Entra I-D, assigned to an Azure resource. The resource uses this identity to obtain short-lived Entra I-D tokens and call any service that supports Entra I-D authentication. Azure handles the entire identity lifecycle including credential rotation — you never see or manage the underlying certificate or secret.

There are two types. A system-assigned Managed Identity is tied to the lifecycle of the Azure resource — it is created when you enable it and deleted when the resource is deleted. Each resource gets one system-assigned identity and it cannot be shared. A user-assigned Managed Identity is an independent Azure resource that persists independently of any compute resource. The same user-assigned identity can be assigned to multiple V-Ms, App Services, or Functions — which is useful when many resources need the same access permissions, or when you want to pre-create an identity before the compute resource exists.

The authentication flow works as follows. You enable Managed Identity on a resource such as a V-M or App Service. Azure creates a service principal in Entra I-D for that resource. You grant the service principal R-B-A-C permissions on the target service — for example, Key Vault Secrets User on a specific vault. When the application needs a token, it calls the Azure Instance Metadata Service at the well-known link-local I-P address 169.254.169.254. This returns a short-lived Entra I-D token that the application uses to call the target service A-P-I. The token is refreshed automatically before it expires.

In practice, you never write this token acquisition code manually. The DefaultAzureCredential class in the Azure S-D-K handles it automatically. It tries a chain of credential sources in order: environment variables for service principal credentials, then Workload Identity for A-K-S pods, then Managed Identity for V-Ms and App Services, then Azure C-L-I credentials for local development, then Azure PowerShell, then Azure Developer C-L-I. This means the same application code works in production using Managed Identity and on your laptop using your az login session — without any conditional logic or configuration changes.

For A-K-S, individual pods cannot directly use the node's V-M-level Managed Identity. The recommended approach is Workload Identity. A Kubernetes Service Account is annotated with the client I-D of a user-assigned Managed Identity. The Workload Identity webhook injects the service account token path and the client I-D as environment variables into the pod. The WorkloadIdentityCredential class in the Azure S-D-K exchanges the Kubernetes service account token for an Entra I-D token via O-I-D-C federation. No secrets are stored in Kubernetes Secrets or pod environment variables.

The Secrets Store C-S-I Driver with the Azure Key Vault provider complements Workload Identity for A-K-S. Instead of calling the Key Vault A-P-I in your application code, you declare a SecretProviderClass resource that maps Key Vault secrets, keys, or certificates to file paths. The C-S-I Driver mounts the values as files in the pod's filesystem at runtime using Workload Identity for authentication. The values are never stored in Kubernetes etcd as Kubernetes Secret objects — they exist only as in-memory volume mounts.

Let us look at a few important patterns.

For App Service and Azure Functions, Key Vault references let you store the Key Vault secret U-R-I as the value of an App Setting instead of the actual secret. The runtime resolves the reference using the App Service's Managed Identity and injects the actual secret value as an environment variable at startup. You configure this by setting the App Setting value to the at-Microsoft-dot-KeyVault syntax with the secret U-R-I. The App Service identity must have the Key Vault Secrets User role on the vault.

For secret rotation, the recommended pattern uses Event Grid. Key Vault emits a SecretNearExpiry event through Event Grid when a secret approaches its expiry date. An Azure Function subscribed to that event generates a new credential — for example, rotating a database password — updates the secret in Key Vault, and optionally restarts dependent services. Applications that always fetch the latest version of the secret by name — without specifying a version — automatically pick up the new value on their next access.

For customer-managed keys, the pattern is: create a Key Vault with purge protection enabled, create a key, grant the Azure service's Managed Identity the Key Vault Crypto User role on that key, and configure the Azure service to use that key for encryption. Azure Storage, Cosmos D-B, S-Q-L Database, and Managed Disks all support this model. If you revoke the key, the encrypted data becomes inaccessible — giving you hard control over your data even in Azure.

To summarise. Key Vault is the central store for all application secrets, cryptographic keys, and certificates. Use the R-B-A-C permission model, not access policies. Enable soft-delete and purge protection. Use private endpoints in production. Enable AuditEvent logging to Log Analytics. Use Managed Identities — system-assigned for single-resource workloads, user-assigned when sharing an identity across multiple resources. Use DefaultAzureCredential in all application code — it works with Managed Identity in production and Azure C-L-I locally. Use Workload Identity and the Secrets Store C-S-I Driver for A-K-S pods. Use Key Vault references in App Service settings to eliminate secrets from application configuration entirely. And use the Event Grid rotation pattern to automate secret rotation without application downtime.

In the next topic, we will look at Microsoft Defender for Cloud and Azure Security Center — the services that assess your security posture, detect threats, and help you meet compliance requirements across your Azure environment.
